  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Morning Sitting
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At the small window I settle myself, leaning back on a blackwood chair.
    My gaunt frame stands like a mountain peak, my temples white as frost.
    I have already tasted medicines countless times, ravaged by illness,
    Yet still I shiver with the cold, forever adjusting my robes.
    Turnips sliced fine and tender greens lie soft upon my plate,
    Freshly cooked barley porridge rises fragrant and pale.
    All the world's ten thousand cares pale before sound sleep and simple food—
    Why then exhaust myself seeking the secret methods of longevity?
  footnotes:
    - The "blackwood chair" (烏床) refers to a dark wood furniture, likely paulownia or similar material, symbolizing the poet's humble, austere dwelling. The poem captures a moment of morning rest and reflection, emphasizing contentment with simplicity over anxious pursuit of health regimens.
